<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910121-0015</DOCNO><DOCID>910121-0015.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Cenvest Inc.:   Bank Says 4th-Quarter Loss   Was Larger Than Expected</HL><DATE>01/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CBCT</CO><IN>EASTERN U.S. BANKS (BAE)BANKS (BNK)</IN><LP>   Cenvest Inc. said it expects a fourth-quarter loss greaterthan anticipated because of poor economic conditions in NewEngland.   The bank-holding company, based in Meriden, Conn., saidthat its loan-loss provision is expected to be about $50million after loan charge-offs.</LP><TEXT>   According to Cenvest, the anticipated fourth-quarter losswill leave the company and its largest subsidiary, CentralBank, with substantially less than the required regulatorycapital minimums.   Cenvest had previously announced that it entered into anagreement with regulators that, among other things, requiresCentral Bank to increase its capital ratios. The company saidthat Central Bank's capital will be substantially less thanit was at the time of that agreement.   Under a business plan developed by new Cenvest management,54 staff positions will be eliminated in an effort to reduceoperating expenses. In addition, the company has proposed amerger of Central Bank and another subsidiary, First CentralBank. But the company said the proposed merger will still notbring Central Bank's capital up to the regulatory minimum.</TEXT></DOC>